

Object detection in UAV aerial imagery has become an important research area due to its applications in traffic monitoring, surveillance, disaster management, agriculture, and smart city development. However, detecting small objects from aerial images remains
challenging because objects occupy only a few pixels and often appear in complex backgrounds.

MFFSODNet introduced a multiscale feature fusion strategy to improve small object detection in UAV aerial images. The authors proposed a Multi-Scale Feature Enhancement Module and a Balanced Dual Feature Pyramid Network to preserve detailed information across 
different scales. Experimental results demonstrated improved detection performance compared to conventional YOLO-based detectors. However, the model was based on older CNN architectures and lacked advanced global context modeling.

YOLO11s-UAV proposed an improved YOLO11s framework specifically designed for UAV-based small object detection. The model introduced improved downsampling operations, feature fusion mechanisms, and lightweight attention modules. The approach achieved higher accuracy 
while maintaining real-time performance. Although the model effectively improved small object detection, it relied primarily on CNN-based feature extraction and did not incorporate modern sequence modeling techniques.

SRTSOD-YOLO further enhanced YOLO11 by introducing advanced feature extraction and feature fusion modules. The proposed architecture utilized Multi-Feature Context Aggregation Modules and Global Attention Convolution Feature Pyramid Networks to preserve fine-grained
object information. Experimental evaluations on UAV datasets demonstrated improved performance in detecting densely distributed small objects. Nevertheless, the model still faced challenges in capturing long-range dependencies among image regions.

SAMYOLO combined Super-Resolution techniques with Vision Mamba architecture to address the issue of low-resolution small objects. The model first enhanced image quality using super-resolution methods and then applied Mamba-based feature extraction for detection. 
Results indicated significant improvements in tiny object detection performance. However, the computational complexity increased due to the additional image enhancement stage.

UAVDet proposed a CNN-Mamba hybrid architecture for efficient small object detection in UAV imagery. The model integrated CNN-based local feature extraction with Vision Mamba-based global context modeling through the Cross Stage Partial Mamba Block (CSPMB). 
In addition, a Tiny Feature Pyramid Network (TFPN) was designed to preserve small object information during feature fusion. Experimental results on VisDrone, UAVDT, and DroneVehicle datasets demonstrated superior performance compared to existing methods.

From the literature survey, it can be observed that recent research trends focus on feature enhancement, attention mechanisms, multiscale fusion, super-resolution, and Vision Mamba architectures. Among these approaches, UAVDet provides a balanced combination of 
accuracy, efficiency, and novelty, making it a suitable baseline for further research. However, opportunities still exist to improve feature attention and object-aware representation learning for enhanced small object detection.
